&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;   I have kind of a steep learning curve, so while the NE602/612 radio
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; works, it has a bigger foot print cuz it requires some extra amplifiers for
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; the audio. I have about 70 of the LM3820 chips, they are an AM radio chip,
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; with all functions except the audio detector. I had trouble getting this
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; chip to work a couple years ago, but since I&#39;ve learned some tricks, like
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; adding the oscillator buffer to keep the freq counter from pulling the
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; frequency way off, other wise, ya think you have the frequency range set,
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; but in use it&#39;s completely out of the AM band, so no stations get picked
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; up.Then I was not aware of how to set up the ferrite rod antenna. The
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 602/612s are $2 something each, the Lm3820--12 cents from B. G. Micro(in
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; tubes of 25). I set up the oscillator last night, then re-drew the
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; schematic. I used a regulated supply to hopefully make the oscialltor more
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; stable, but the chip will function on 12 volts-besides, come to think about
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; it, it has a built in regulator, so the 8V regulator is overkill, maybe even
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; harmful in that  the internal regulator wouldn&#39;t have enough head room.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;  Frank-S
